{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600568/1930102801/0174.xml":{"full_text":"SLIGHT DROP NOTED\nIN GAS EARNINGS\nP. Phone Co. Also Has\nj Lower September Net.\nLocal Calls Increasing.\nBT EDWARD C. STONE.\nPractically no change took place in\ntfre net Income of the Washington Oas j\nlight Co., in September, 1930, com\npared with the corresponding month\na year ago. Net profits were $32,150.75,\n\u2022gainst $32,951.03, a slight drop of S7OO,\naccording to the report filed today with\nthe Public Utilities Commission.\nOperating revenues amounted to\nM 8,954.16. against $393,623.96 in Sep\ntember, 1929. Operating expenses re\nquired $28\u201d,285.77, compared with\n$977,939.92, leaving total operating\nrevenues of $88,660.07, in comparison\nwith $89,072.10 last year.\nIncome from other sources gave the\ngas company a gross corporate income\nof $91,305.92, against $93,072.10 a year\nago. Interest and other deductions\namounted to $59,155.17, compared with\n$60,121.07 a year ago.\nFor the nine months, of 1930. the gas\ncompany reported total operating rev\nenues aounting to $4,081,197.84, against\n$4,144,685.06. while revenue deductions\nrequired $2,936,128.72, compared with\n$2,971,139.29. leaving an operating In\ncome of $1,145,069.12, compared with\n$1,173,545.77.\nOross corporate income for the year\nto date reached $1,163,501.73. against\n$1,198,636.21 a year ago. In the same\nperiod other deductions such as bond\ninterest etc. absorbed $550,679.04, In\ncomparison with $546,075.35. lerving a\ntotal net Income for the nine months\namounting to $612,822.69. compared\nwith the higher net return last year\nOs $652,560.86.\nA study of the Report indicates that\nthe falling off in earnings is due to\nlower sales of gas so far this year.\nThe main factors in the decline are\nthe let-up in business compared with\nlast year and in the Intensely hot\nSummer.\nC. A P. Phone Net Slumps.\nThe balance net operating income of\nthe Chesapeake St Potomac Telephone\n00. in September was $97,119, which\nwas a decrease of $5,223 over the same\nmonth last year, the report of opera\ntions Just filed with the Public Utilities\nCommission today shows.\nNet operating income for the nine\nmonths ending September 30 amounted\nto $902,687, which is a decrease of $36,-\n335 over the same period last year.\nTelephone operating revenues for the\nmonth of September were $690,645,\nr with expenses of $593,007. Operating in\ncome, after deducting taxes and un\ncollectibles was $141,103.\nTelephone operating revenues for the\nnine months ending September 30 were\n$6,396,889, with expenses of $4,705,138,\nmaking operating income after deduct\ning taxes and uncollectibles $1,302,843.\nTaxes for Sept- ,l>er aiVunted to $43.-\n15$. Taxes for the nine months end\ning September 30 amounted to $415,963.\nCapital expenditures for new plant\nand equipment during the first nine\nmonths of the year amounted to $2,721,-\n325. Oross retirements during this pe\nriod were $2,628,924, making net ad\nditions $91,405. Net additions to plant\nfor the 12 months ending September\n30, amounted to $774,439.\nTelephone Calls Increase.\nTelephone calls in Washington in\ncreased 6.7 per cent in September over\nths same month of last year. 15,604.145\ncalls being made. At the close of busi\nness September 30. there were 163,736\ntelephones in Washington.\nTne officers and directors of the tele\nphone company visited the Western\nIS&ctric Co.'s plant at Point Breeze,\nBaltimore, yesterday, where they were\nthe guests of W. H. Meese, vice presi\ndent and works manager.\nThose from Washington who inspected\nthe plant were Edwin C. Graham. John\nPoole. B. Francis Saul. W. W. Everett,\nRobert V. Fleming, Merle Thorp, Dr.\nGilbert Grosvenor, Lloyd B. Wilson,\nEugene S. Wilson, Philip O. Coffin and\nMarshall D. Sedam, directors, and Wal\nter B. Clarkson, vice president and sec\nretary; John C. Koons, vice president,\nand R. A. Van Orsdel, general counsel.\nAccompanying the officers and di\nrectors on the inspection of the manu\nfacturing plant were the following\ndirectors and officers of the Chesapeake\nSt Potomac Telephone Co. of Baltimore\nCity: Charles H. Carter, Henry M. War\nfield, R. Howard Bland, William G.\nBaker and Alexander Armstrong, di\nrectors, and Frederick J. Irish, general\nmanager, and E. L. Flora nee, general\n4 commercial manager.\nThe Western Electric plant in Balti\nmore is engaged almost entirely in the\nmanufacture of telephone supplies for\nthe associated Bell companies. Much\nof the cable and wire used by the local\ntelephone company is manufactured\nthere.\nGeorgetown Gas Net Higher.\nThe Georgetown Gas Co. reported to\nthe Public Utilities Commission today\na good increase in net earnings for the\nmonth of September. Net corporate in\ncome amounted to $9,589.83, against\n$6,674.25 in September, 1929.\nThe company reported September\noperating revenues as $70,360.70, against\n$66,942.25 in the same month last year.\nOperating expenses totaled $53,819.09,\nagainst $52,744.84 a yesr ago. This\nleft an operating net of $13,059.70, j\n\u2022gainst $9.959 45.\nThe company reported a substantial i\ngain in earnings for the first nine\nmonths of the present year. Operating\nrevenues amounted to $770,659.93,\ncompared with $721,262.41 a year ago.\nOperating expenses totaled $570,164.48,\ncompared with $545,734.93.\nAfter the usual revenue deductions i\nthe Georgetown company had an in\ncome from operations amounting to\n$165,904 27, against $139,880.38. The\ncorporation had more than SII,OOO as\nnon-operating income, took out the\nusual deductions for bond Interest, etc.,\nand then had a total net income for the\nnine months of $132,442.72, in com\nparison with the lower figure of $107.-\n194.53 in the first nine months of 1929.\nVD. C. Exchange More Active.\nTrading was improved on the Wash\nington Stock Exchange today, being\ndivided about equally between bonds\nant' stocks.\nCapitral Traction stock was stronger,\n20 shares only being traded in and selling\nat 50%. In connection with this stock\nIt ls interesting to note that an invest\nment firm recently made a bid for 1,000\nshares at 51, and that no such amount\nof the stock was available at that price.\nPotomac Electric s'i per cent pref\nerred sold at 108 V*. Railway Electric\npreferred moved at 98 and Mergen\nthaler Linotype came out at 89%. Two\nbank stocks appeared on the board.\nCommercial National selling at 225 and\nUnion-Trust at 233.\nBonds remained around recent levels.\nTraction, Washington Gas, Washington\nRailway St Electric and Potomac Power\nIssues all figuring in the day s transac\ntions.\n\nSAW SILK FUTURES.\nNEW YORK. October 28 (Special).\u2014\nRaw silk futures were 4 to 12 points\nlower at the opening today, influenced\nby the weakness in the Far Eastern\nmarkets, with Yokohama 24 to 34 lower\nand Kobe off 28 to 33. There were 80\ntransferable notices Issued today, the\nfirst this month. Commission house in\nterests and uptown operators seemed to\nbe the buyers, with the selling coming\nv from houses which usually act for man\nufacturers and from importers.\n\nDr. J. W> Finch, dean of mining at the\nUniversity of Idaho, will supervise the\nwriting of a memorial volume on Rocky\nf' Mountain ore deposit*.\nFINANCIAL.\nI NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE I\nReceived by Private Wire Direct to The Star Office.\nNote\u2014All stocks are sold In one hundred-share lots\nexcepting those designated by the letter a (80s) (2505)\nwhich shows those stocks to be sold In odd lots only.\nIndiviloal sales compiled to 12:08\u2014complete in 5:30 Edition.\n\u2014Pro? IDSO\u2014> Stock and Uatea\u2014 Prov\ndish. Low Dividend Rata Add 00. Hleh. Low. Clom. Clou,\nk 66 40 Abraham Strauaa.... 1 42 42 42 40\n37% 19% Adams Exp (1.\u00ab0>... 23 22 21% 21% 21%\n94 85H Adams Exp pf (5)... 10a 87% 87% 87% 87%\n1% Ahumada Lead l\n156% 96% Air Reduction (t4H) 48 110% 107% 108 109%\n36 10 Air Way El Ap (114) 1 10% 10% 10% 10\n9% 4